SIMPLE: snick
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snick
<hw>Snick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>snick</ets> a notch; cf. Icel. <ets>snikka</ets> nick, cut.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A small cut or mark.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>A slight hit or tip of the
ball, often unintentional.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Fiber)</fld> <def>A knot or irregularity in
yarn.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Furriery)</fld> <def>A snip or cut, as in the hair
of a beast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Snick and snee</b></col> <ety>[cf. D. <ets>snee</ets>,
<ets>snede</ets>, a cut]</ety>, <cd>a combat with knives.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snick
<hw>Snick</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Snicked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Snicking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut slightly; to
strike, or strike off, as by cutting.</def> <rj><au>H.
Kingsley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>To hit (a ball) lightly.</def>
<rj><au>R. A. Proctor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Snick
<hw>Snick</hw>, <pos>n. & v. t.</pos> <def>See <er>Sneck</er>.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Snick up</b></col>, <cd>shut up; silenced. See <xex>Sneck
up</xex>, under <er>Sneck</er>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give him money, George, and let him go <qex>snick up</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Snicker</ent>⟦br⟧
